ğŸ™What a CNAME Record is (one name pointing to another name)
        CNAME = Canonical Name
        It means:
        â€œThis name is just an alias of another name.â€
        Example:
        www.example.com â†’ example.com
        Meaning:
        www.example.com does NOT have its own IP
        It simply points to example.com
        Then DNS looks up the A/AAAA record of example.com

ğŸ™What an MX Record is (how emails find your mail server)
         MX = Mail Exchange
        MX records tell the internet:
        ğŸ‘‰ â€œWhere should emails for this domain be delivered?â€
        Example:
        example.com â†’ mail.google.com (priority 1)
        Meaning:
        Emails sent to @example.com go to Googleâ€™s mail servers
        ğŸ“Œ MX records only affect email, not websites.

ğŸ™What a TXT Record is (extra information and verification)
                TXT = Text
                Used to store:               
                Domain ownership verification                
                Email security (SPF, DKIM, DMARC)                
                App integrations               
                Example:               
                TXT: "google-site-verification=abc123"
ğŸ§  TXT is like a note attached to your domain saying:
â€œYes, I approve this service.â€

ğŸ™How all DNS records work together for one website
        Letâ€™s say your domain is myshop.com        
        Step-by-step what happens:        
        Browser asks:
